In another investigation, Zhao et al.108 highlighted the activation of PMS by Fe-Al LDH to efficiently degrade Bisphenol A (BPA). Notably, Mӧssbauer spectroscopy was used to explain the surface transformation of Fe-Al LDH after the catalytic reaction. It was observed from the Mӧssbauer spectrum of Fe-Al LDH that there were two species of Fe2+ (Fe–O–Fe and Fe-O-Al)109,110. Unequivocally, the electronegativity of Fe2+ in Fe–O–Fe is lower than Fe-O-Al owing to the higher electron-withdrawing property of Fe than Al. Furthermore, the proportions of Fe–O–Fe and Fe-O-Al in Fe-Al LDH were 15% and 62%, respectively, with a small proportion of Fe3+ that may be due to the sample oxidation throughout the measurement. The Mӧssbauer spectrum of the transformed Fe-Al LDH after the BPA degradation showed that the proportion of Fe2+ in both species decreased with an increase in the formed Fe3+. This finding designated the participation of Fe2+ in both reactive species which may be attributed to the good conductivity of the whole metal layer. Moreover, to scrutinize the impact of time on the active species during the activation of PMS, Fe-Al LDH/PMS was examined by an in-situ electron paramagnetic resonance (EPR) test. It was observed that there were three active species (∙OH\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
