In another investigation, Yang et al.61 fabricated a series of ComFen-LDHs with different molar ratios between Co and Fe through the combination of in situ exfoliation and co-precipitation methods. Such an innovative technique resulted in the formation of a thinner structure of ComFen-LDHs with high stability, prevented the leaching of Co and Fe, and increased the active sites. The XRD patterns showed an enhancement in the crystallinity of ComFen-LDHs with raising the Co2+ content. On the contrary, the increase in the Fe3+ ratio diminished the peak intensity of ComFen-LDHs, which may be attributed to the ability of Fe3+ of inhibiting the crystallization in acidic conditions. Furthermore, the low interlayer spacing (7.63) of Co1Fe1-LDHs compared to other fabricated LDHs reflected its thinner structure. Noteworthy, the increase in the Co2+ content improved the degradation efficiency of ciprofloxacin (CIP) up to 86.9%. Furthermore, it was found that the optimum pH of the CIP degradation by Co1Fe1-LDHs/PMS was in the range of 5–9. This finding could be explained by the leaching of Co2+ and Fe3+ at pH < 3, whereas at pH 11, there was an electrostatic repulsion force between the dominant species of PMS (SO52−\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
